  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I recognize a fake solar panel?",
  "response": "Recognizing a fake solar panel can help you avoid poor-quality products and ensure that you are investing in a reliable, efficient system. Here are some tips to help you identify a fake or subpar solar panel:\n\n1. **Check Manufacturer Credentials**:\n   - Research the manufacturer. Established brands often have a history of reliability and customer support.\n   - Look for certifications from organizations such as UL (Underwriters Laboratories), IEC (International Electrotechnical Commission), and others.\n\n2. **Review Product Specifications**:\n   - Compare the specifications (wattage, efficiency, dimensions) with those of models from credible manufacturers. Extremely low prices for high-efficiency panels can be a red flag.\n\n3. **Inspect Build Quality**:\n   - Examine the panels for any signs of poor craftsmanship. Check the solder joints, frame, and backsheet for quality finishes.\n   - Authentic panels typically have a robust construction that can withstand environmental factors.\n\n4. **Look for Labels and Certifications**:\n   - Genuine solar panels usually have labels that showcase compliance with safety and performance standards. Look for certification labels on the back of the panel.\n   - Ensure that the serial number is present and that the panel has been registered with a reputable company.\n\n5. **Evaluate the Warranty**:\n   - Trusted manufacturers provide long warranties for their products (often 25 years). Be cautious of panels offered with unusually short warranties or no warranty at all.\n\n6. **Ask for Documentation**:\n   - Request installation and performance data, along with test results. Legitimate products should come with proper documentation and performance history.\n\n7. **Verify Installation and Support Services**:\n   - Check if the company offers installation services and support. Fake or unreliable manufacturers may not provide assistance after the purchase.\n\n8. **Check Reviews and Testimonials**:\n   - Look for user reviews and testimonials, but verify them through independent sources rather than only the manufacturer's website.\n\n9. **Inspect the Price**:\n   - If the price is too good to be true compared to other products on the market, it might be a fake or low-quality product. \n\n10. **Trust Your Instincts**:\n    - If something feels off about the purchase\u2014be it through a lack of information, suspiciously low pricing, or unresponsive customer service\u2014consider looking elsewhere.\n\nBy applying these considerations, you can improve your chances of recognizing a genuine solar panel and make a more informed buying decision.",
